{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503298"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2004"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2004"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.02,0.32,0.24,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92554"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2004"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75869"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1009"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31701"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92554"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man is being reviewed in a hospital ward. He is from home, living with his wife, and recently admitted with worsening symptoms of dementia. His wife says that he has become increasingly paranoid and falsely accusing her of infidelity, as he believes he catches glimpses of her lover\u2019s shadow creeping around the house at night. His moods have become more labile, and she is worried things may soon turn violent. She is now unable to care for him at home due to the extent of his mistrust in her, which has become even more problematic of late due to an increased frequency of falls and impaired mobility. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn the ward, he is frequently agitated and aggressive despite non-pharmacological de-escalation techniques, to the point where he poses a danger to others.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sedating medications would be most suitable in this patient until he is able to undergo further assessment and management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olanzapine","Clozapine","Quetiapine","Risperidone","Haloperidol"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u2019s presentation is suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003ELewy Body Dementia\u003C/strong\u003E, and he is therefore at risk of neuroleptic hypersensitivity, making him particularly vulnerable to the extra-pyramidal side effects (EPSEs) of anti-psychotics. While the newer agents (such as olanzapine, clozapine, quetiapine, risperidone) are more likely to be associated with metabolic adverse effects, and less so the EPSEs of the first generation anti-psychotics (such as haloperidol), low-dose quetiapine is the preferred agent in this setting due to the relatively lower rate of EPSEs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low-dose quetiapine is the preferred agent in Lewy Body Dementia due to the relatively lower rate of extra-pyramidal side effects."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook, 2020. \u2018Antipsychotics\u2019, accessed 23/4/20,"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75869"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2004"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75869"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T11:36:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T11:36:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2